        <guid>https://whhong-research.github.io/en/p/sam-crack-segmentation-experiments-prompt-point-strategies-and-performance-evaluation/</guid>
        <description>&lt;img src="https://whhong-research.github.io/p/sam%E8%A3%82%E7%BC%9D%E5%88%86%E5%89%B2%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E6%8F%90%E7%A4%BA%E7%82%B9%E7%AD%96%E7%95%A5%E4%B8%8E%E6%80%A7%E8%83%BD%E8%AF%84%E4%BC%B0/004_True10_conf58.15.png" alt="Featured image of post SAM Crack Segmentation Experiments: Prompt Point Strategies and Performance Evaluation" /&gt;&lt;h1 id=&#34;experiment-objectives-and-background&#34;&gt;Experiment Objectives and Background
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;This experiment aims to explore the application of the Segment Anything Model (SAM) in crack image segmentation tasks, with a focus on investigating how different prompt point strategies affect segmentation quality. Through systematic testing of positive and negative points, we have summarized a series of practical optimization strategies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;prompt-point-strategy-experiments&#34;&gt;Prompt Point Strategy Experiments
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-optimization-role-of-negative-points&#34;&gt;The Optimization Role of Negative Points
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;In practical testing, when manually inputting relatively accurate crack prompt points, and when the crack clearly divides the image into two parts, using only positive points may cause SAM to incorrectly identify large road surface areas as segmentation targets. In such cases, adding two negative points in the mask region can significantly improve segmentation results and accurately identify the crack area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Finding&lt;/strong&gt;: Properly setting a small number of negative points can effectively constrain SAM&amp;rsquo;s segmentation range and significantly improve crack identification accuracy.&lt;/p&gt;
